desc:
CCF is looking to parse Reverse Proxy events from Bluecoat

These event types will be additional JSON array within the BLUECOAT_WEBPROXY logs so we will need to determine if it makes sense to extend the current default parser or create a customer specific parser to handle them. Also, we are not currently ingesting these events as that is scheduled to happen very soon.

Question 1: What is the recommended approach extend the current default parser? Or create customer specific parser for the reverse proxy events?  
re: We're working to move away from customer-specific parsers wherever possible

**
ATENTION: we must figure out these questions to have a better defined scope on this task
**

**
Question 1: Why is the parser failing to parse the new events?
**
According to this document, https://wikileaks.org/spyfiles/document/bluecoat/268_blue-coat-systems-sg-appliance-volume-8-access-logging/268_blue-coat-systems-sg-appliance-volume-8-access-logging.pdf
There are 16 different default types of logs formats, this is a different type of those.
For most modern versions ( after Symantec acquisition) there are 4 different log formats:
https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/dam/broadcom/techdocs/symantec-security-software/web-and-network-security/proxysg/6-7/generated-pdfs/SGOSAdmin67.pdf ( page 699)

**
Question 2: Is that possible to explain what the reverse proxy events look like? Are these reverse proxy events? What is the difference between web proxy and reverse proxy events?
**
According to this document:
https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/dam/broadcom/techdocs/symantec-security-software/web-and-network-security/proxysg/common/LogFieldsSubs.pdf
For version 6.5.x and above there are some log fields that only exist when is a reverse proxy. But in a general way, for the older versions, it's no possible.

**
Question 3: What is the recommended approach to extend the current default parser? Or create a customer-specific parser for the reverse proxy events?
**
Since there is no way to have sure if the received samples are reverse proxy samples. I Do believe that is better to extend the current default parser.

The AWS_CLOUDTRAIL parser was written as a native parser because it needed a for loop to go through the events in the raw log. Since "for loops" are now supported on CBN, convert the AWS_CLOUDTRAIL parser to CBN. Also, Fishtech asked for parsing support for the following EventNames as well:

```
"eventName":"Decrypt"

"eventName":"Encrypt"

"eventName":"CreateGrant"

"eventName":"RetireGrant"

"eventName":"RevokeGrant"

"eventName": "CreateKey"

"eventName": "DescribeKey"
```

Make sure to include fields such as Usernames, AWS Account IDs and S3 Bucket Names (if there are any).

The current native parser supports the Event Names listed on the eventNameToPopulateUdmFunc [mapping](https://source.corp.google.com/piper///depot/google3/googlex/security/malachite/normalizers/nativeparser/aws_cloudtrail.go;l=83-106;bpv=1).

It also has support for Event Names that start with Get*, List* and Describe*. [Here](https://source.corp.google.com/piper///depot/google3/googlex/security/malachite/normalizers/nativeparser/aws_cloudtrail.go;bpv=1;l=23)

desc:
**WIP**

The current default CBN for GMAIL_LOGS always generates one single security_result payload merging all the info into it but we probably should consider to have multiple security_result, one for each action/policy who generates a specific outcome.

Let's take as example the attached log sample and its relative textproto: the log sample contains both spam info and triggered policy rule info, they represent two distinct actions on the email but textproto shows them under the same security_result. We should consider to have a output like that:

```
  security_result: {
     category: MAIL_SPAM
     category: MAIL_PHISHING
     summary: <spam classification reason>
  }
  security_result: {
     rule_id: "8"
     rule_name: "subject with EXT prefix"
     summary: "Content compliance"
  }
```

NOTE: <spam classification reason> is not currently parsed for a bug in the CBN. This (GMAIL_LOGS/default/default.conf line 885) should be here ( GMAIL_LOGS/default/default.conf line 1095).

The benefit to have a security_result.summary for spam events is that, since in case of malware we set a significant alert, security_result.summary will be the alert name visible in Enterprise Insight.

----
Chat:
*Diego*: Let me see if I understand. Are you saying that the bug is because of the position in the code of the line 885, or that the snippet (~885-891) should be inside the include file?

*gcuratola*: I meant that the field reason in the CBN is populated after the assignment of reason to _security_result.description so it won't be added to the final UDM event. However this is only for "spam classification reason" the main purpose of the bug is to have multiple security_result sections in the UDM event, one for each action/policy who generates a specific outcome.


----

desc:
**WIP**



The update is to use (a) jsonPayload.vmProjectId instead of (b) resource.labels.project_id. The reasoning being that (b) is the GCP Project that is generating the logs, and usually that's a Shared VPC (a central project), whereas (a) is the source GCP project the VM is attached. This is a more intuative mapping for the (i) principal.namespace as well as (ii) principal.cloud.project.name

adding metadata.product_name of "Cloud DNS" would be great too please as it's missing in Looker Dashboards.

Example log from my test org (no sensitive, not customer data)

**
{
  "insertId": "1034e7ye5dex6",
  "jsonPayload": {
    "authAnswer": true,
    "protocol": "UDP",

Adding some context for Device User, Profile User, Trigger User, and content size in case it helps:
Adding some context for Device User, Profile User, Trigger User, and content size in case it helps:
device_user - This is the machine user, eg the username of the user logged into the device (eg, user logged into the windows)
profile_user - The Chrome browser profile of the current user (this will be the email of the user signed into the profile if there is one, otherwise, it will be the name given to the profile by the user)
trigger_User - The username relating to the event (eg, if it's a password reuse event, the trigger user is the user name that the password belongs to)
context_size - the size of the content downloaded, in bytes

go/udm:cloudy has event types for interacting with cloud resources in addition to USER_LOGIN which will likely be a much better fit than the existing ones.

Can leverage existing sample logs in code search for this enhancement, user specific data sets not required.

Related issue: b/159167920
Similar issue: b/160260894
name: MICROSOFT_CASB: Fix -> Use go/udm:cloudy Event Types Instead of FILE_...
